elements.text:
1. Blue-Green Deployment

Concept: Maintain two identical production environments
How it works:

Blue = Current live environment
Green = New version deployment
Test Green thoroughly
Switch traffic from Blue to Green instantly
Keep Blue as backup for quick rollback

Benefits:

* Zero downtime
* Instant rollback capability
* Full testing before go-live

elements.text:
What Are Deployment Strategies?

Deployment strategies are different approaches 
to releasing new versions of your application to users.

Why do we need them?

* Minimize downtime
* Reduce risk of breaking changes
* Ensure smooth user experience
* Enable quick rollbacks if issues occur

What Are Deployment Strategies?

Deployment strategies are different approaches 
to releasing new versions of your application to users.

Why do we need them?

* Minimize downtime
* Reduce risk of breaking changes
* Ensure smooth user experience
* Enable quick rollbacks if issues occur

elements.text:
The Problem with Traditional Deployment

Traditional "All-at-Once" Deployment:

Stop old version → Deploy new version → Start new version

Problems:

* Downtime during deployment
* If something breaks, all users affected
* Hard to rollback quickly
* No way to test with real users gradually

elements.text:
2. Rolling Deployment

Concept: Gradually replace instances of the old version with the new version
How it works:

1. Start with multiple instances running old version
2. Replace one instance at a time with new version
3. Continue until all instances are updated
4. Monitor health at each step

Benefits:

* No downtime
* Gradual transition
* Can pause/rollback at any point
* Requires less infrastructure than Blue-Green

elements.text:
3. Canary Deployment

Concept: Release new version to a small subset of users first
How it works:

1. Deploy new version to small percentage of servers (e.g., 5%)
2. Route small portion of traffic to new version
3. Monitor metrics, errors, user feedback
4. Gradually increase traffic if everything looks good
Rollback if issues detected

Benefits:

* Real user testing with minimal risk
* Early detection of issues
* Gradual confidence building

elements.text:
4. Shadow Deployment

Concept: Run new version alongside old version, but don't serve traffic to users
How it works:

1. Deploy new version parallel to current version
2. Copy (shadow) real production traffic to new version
3. Compare responses and performance
4. Users only see responses from old version
5. Switch traffic once confident new version works

Benefits:

* Test with real production data
* Zero user impact during testing
* Performance comparison under real load

elements.text:
5. A/B Testing Deployment

Concept: Deploy different versions to different user groups to compare performance
How it works:

1. Split users into groups (A and B)
2. Deploy version 1 to group A
3. Deploy version 2 to group B
4. Measure key metrics (conversion, performance, etc.)
5. Choose winning version for full deployment

Benefits:

* Data-driven decisions
* Compare business metrics
* Understand user preferences

elements.text:
6. Feature Flags (Feature Toggles)

Concept: Control feature visibility without deploying new code
How it works:

1. Deploy code with features "turned off"
2. Use configuration to enable/disable features
3. Gradually roll out features to user segments
4. Instant rollback by flipping flag

Benefits:

* Decouple deployment from feature release
* Instant feature rollback
* Gradual feature rollout
* A/B testing capabilities
